segments.text: Okay.

And the youngest son, Billy, of course, he wasn't, because he had an old mean daddy that said what he thought, for various reasons, that being the principal one, he wasn't accepted into the school of veterinary medicine at A&M.
Got his degree in animal science down there.
I told him, I said, well, there are other ways to make a living besides running their medicine.
He says, I'll decide if it takes me all my life, I'm going to be a veterinarian.
I said, well, I'm going to spend all my life helping you.
So he's accepted at the University of the Philippines.
How he got in there, I don't know, but he was accepted out there.
So we flew out there, and he went to the University of the Philippines for two years.
And he'd just come back in after his second year out there, and the telephone rang one day.
He said, this is Dr. Niemeyer at the University of Missouri.
We have an opening up here, and we're offering you a position in the College of Veterinary Medicine.
He said, well, I don't know, Dr. Niemeyer.
I'm pretty happy where I am, but I'll come up and talk to you.
He says, that's what I want you to do.
So he went up there.

and decided to enroll in the University of Missouri went through and in his senior year there's some lady up there that gives a little stipend to the outstanding equine veterinary student senior veterinary student and it's that student is selected by the professor and he was selected the outstanding
equine veterinary student at the University of Missouri the year he graduated.
And he came back here.
I tell my Texas, you don't mind, I tell my Texas A&M friends that they did me a great favor.
They made my son go to another school and get a good education.
But anyway, he has come back here and he's done a tremendous job.
He has in about, how long has he been back here?
Three years?
Four years?
No, he's been back.
Four years?
No, he was married five years in July, so he's been back over five years.
Well, he graduated in 81, didn't he?
Or 80?
All right.
Well, he's been back five years.
And I tell people he just messed up my practice.
When he came back, I had my practice...
I had it figured out where I was taking care of my friends and special people, and he came back and said, no, Dad, you're supposed to try to take care of everybody.
And he's shriveled our practice.
Shriveled it, yeah.
Shriveled it, and he's, of course, he's brought in some young veterinarians with him.
He has three other young veterinarians with him.
Now, that's another thing.
These young people communicate with this generation better than I do.
Uh-huh, yeah.
I don't know why.
I don't know why.
But they can sell them, and they can relate, and they communicate.
He can just convince people, you know, if he decides this is what he's supposed to do, well, he can just tell them, and that's the way it goes.
And sometimes they'll argue back and forth with me.
He's just more convincing, just smarter, I guess.
I guess it's his mother in him.
Well, I do want to say to your favor, and I've always been impressed with individuals who are complimentary toward their parents.
And I talked to him the other day, and first I apologized to him for calling him and, you know, interrupting his day and so forth and so on.
He said, no problem.
And then I told him what's that, and he was very complimentary of you both.
And I think that that is a real...
something that is very nice.
Well, we appreciate that.
And he's just alert, bright, to the point, pleasant, and all that sort of good thing.
I'd like to ask, go ahead.
We're very fortunate.
We've never had any problem with either one of our boys.
Well, that's wonderful.
Sure have.
Dub's quite a little younger than you are, isn't he?
He is.
Because he graduated in the 50s.
He is.
There is about 15 years difference.
That's a lot.
Usually families aren't, you know, nowadays they have the three children and quit right then and there.
That's right.
That's right.
Yes.
I'd like to ask you two questions more or less in closing, plus anything else after that you may want to say.
Do you have any observations on your year as president of the Texas Veterinary Medical Association?
I wasn't president of the Texas Veterinary Medical Association.
I was in the chairs.
I think I was maybe first or second vice president.
And I was elected to the board of the ABMA.
I didn't go on through because I just didn't have the time.
Well, you're certainly right.
OK, my next question is going to be, what are your observations on your years
I mean, I know it wasn't just one year, you know, you're president-elect, etc., etc., etc., but that's the year you get knocked around.
Well, and you do.
You run over a lot of people if you think you're doing what's right, you know, and you make enemies and friends, but...
I wouldn't take anything for that year.
It was a wonderful year, and I've made friends all over this country and foreign friends.
What happened specifically?
I wouldn't go through it again.
What happened specifically?
I mean, is there any highlight?
Oh, I guess probably the highlight of my...
My tenure, shall we say, as president of the ABMA was when I went to Washington and visited with President Kennedy.
You were in the chair of the centennial year of the association.
Yeah, that's right, too.
That was the centennial year.
You must have been 62 then, is that right?
We had asked Graham Purcell to introduce a resolution in Congress setting aside veterinary medical week because of our 100th anniversary.
Why, he says, sure, I'll do that.
And he got up there, and he found out that there hadn't been one of those things put through Congress
Franklin Roosevelt's days and he didn't let that deter him he just kept on and I appeared before two or three a Senate committee and a House committee too requesting this and
Oh, I had old Senator Dirksen on my side, and gosh, I made a lot of friends up there, and we got the darn thing passed.
We don't know how.
Well, that was a highlight.
She brought it up, too.
We don't know how it happened.
Well, that's tremendous.
But we got that thing passed, and we were in New York at the AVMA meeting, and Graham was down there.
He was attending with us.
We had asked him to come down.
And he had a call that the president was going to sign this proclamation the next morning at 9 o'clock in Washington, D.C.
So he and I got on a commuter plane and flew to Washington.
And I had one of these little...
knick-knack things, commemorative outfit.
Medallion.
Medallion.
That's what I was trying to say.
Commemorating our 100th.
ABMA medallion.
Yeah.
Centennial medallion.
Centennial medallion.
That's what it was.
So I was carrying it with me, and I was afraid when we walked into the White House that they'd shake us down and take it away from us, but nobody said anything.
We walked in, and they took us into the Senate
room first, the cabinet room first, and we sat down there, and there was some John Kennedy matches, so we both got us a box of John Kennedy matches.

And then here comes an old boy, I thought he was a janitor or somebody, and he took us into the fish room, and he says, now, I said, that's a beat-up old desk right there, and he said, yeah, that's a desk that the
that President Kennedy's father gave him when he was elected to the legislature, when he was in the House, I believe.
And I says, what's that old deer head over there?
And he said, that's the deer that President Kennedy killed on Vice President Johnson's ranch last fall.
I said, well, that's the best.
That's the best job I ever saw on a head like that.
Mounting a deer head?
Mounting.
I said, that's the best mounting I ever saw on him.
Because I said, you know, there's just no signs of those rope burns on that neck.
Well, he didn't think that was very funny.
Come to find out, he was the president's secretary about the second...
one second secretary down.
So we walked out of there and we started down the hall to the Rose Room and there was that old skin-headed boy and I said, hell, I've seen that old boy.
And I walked up and shook hands with him.
I said, I'm Dan Anderson.
He says, I'm Dean Rusk.
Dean Rusk.
Secretary of State.
Yeah, Secretary of State.
And I turned to old Graham and
I said, these sure are friendly people.
He says, oh, yeah, they don't have anything to worry about except when somebody's going to drop an atomic bomb on us or something like that.
That's about all they have to worry about.
So I walked on down into the room and introduced me to Kennedy, and he sat down and took about a half a dozen pens to sign that thing.
Did you?
Oh, yeah.
Hope you still have it.
Yeah, we still have it somewhere.
And...
So I'd asked Graham, I said, now, when do I give this thing to him?
And I don't know, you may not get a chance to.
Well, I says, yeah, I'll get a chance to.

And he was in the back in the middle of his writing, and I said, well, Mr. President, I know you get a lot of this kind of crap, but we sincerely want you to have it as a token of our appreciation for what you've done, or something like that.
Later, Graham said, no you didn't say crap, it was even worse, you said junk.
So then I got to talking to the president about his wife's little dog and we visited there a few minutes.
And Graham was embarrassed and he walked off.
And he says, you know, I turned and looked and the president had his arm around Ben's shoulder.
And we finally left and he says, you've embarrassed me so it'll take me a year to get back in this place.
I said, Graham, I ain't coming back.
I had to get everything I wanted.
While you were here?
Oh, yeah, yeah.
And another...
Another thing that I wasn't supposed to, we had the president's picture on our brochure, you know, for the centennial meeting.
And I said, Mr. President, I sure would like to have your autograph on it to Dr. Dan Anderson with regards, John F. Kennedy.
And I said, you know, I have two boys.
I've just got to have another one.
I got two of his autographs, and you're not supposed to ask the president for his autograph.
Oh, is that right?
I just found it out, but I got it.
Yeah, old Graham says, you've messed me up so it'll take me a year to get back here.
Well, I'll tell you, the only thing you could have done for Graham that would have improved the whole situation, you should have invited the president to Dallas.
We've got an awful nice city called Dallas down there in Texas.
We'd just be dying to have you come down.
But somebody else took care of that.
Someone else.
I guess LBJ invited him over.
Yeah.
Well, those were wonderful.
That was certainly a highlight.
You know, wasn't it quite a strain?
You remember, who was our AVMA president?
Our president and...
treasure for so long, uh, uh, was in Minnesota then moved to Washington.
Oh, uh, oh, oh, name's right on the tip of my tongue.
The, you mean the treasure?
Yes, he was AVMA treasure for several years.
Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah.
He was from Minnesota.
He's a good friend of mine, and he died here.
About three or four years ago.
Don, Don... Spangler.
Don Spangler.
Yeah.
He was a real nice fella, and he came down here and addressed the AVMA, the TVMA, in 65 when I took over.
Yeah.
And I, after we finished, I said, Don, you look beat.
I said, are you going to be busy for a couple days?
And he says, well, yeah.
He says, I've got to get back up to the snowdrift, but I don't have to be there until the day after tomorrow.
And I said, why don't you come on down to the son of Mac Allen and just rest for a little bit?
And he says, that's us.
You know, we met in Corpus Christi.
He said, that's a splendid idea.
I said, okay, we'll meet down there, and we'll put you up in the Holiday Inn and just come on down.
So he came down there and
checked in, and in about ten minutes he was dressed out in the sun on one of those chaise lounges, you know, that they have out there around the swimming pool.
And I said, you know, we want to show you around the valley here, so as soon as you finish here and get your clothes on, we'll take you a little tour.
And he says,
You aren't going to do any such thing.
He says, I'm just going to sit out here this afternoon and I'm going to soak up this sun.
I'm going to forget about all those snowdrifts and I'm going to relax so I can go back to the snow and see a few more meetings.
He says, but, if you will, please.

If you would take my Chrysler down to the Chrysler agency and get this and this and this and this done, because every place I've gone, you know, it was all snowed in underneath, and they couldn't do anything with it.
And he says, I want you to get the oil chains and grease, the alignment fixed and all that sort of thing.
Could you do that for me?
And I said, yeah, sure can.
So I went down there.
It took all afternoon to get all that done, you know, and I brought it back.
And I says, Don, what can I do for you?
And he says, you've done it all for me.
He says, I just feel wonderful.
He says, I'm just ready to go back after it again.
So that was kind of the way it was during your year, wasn't it?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, it was hectic.
I would fly out of here and make meetings.
And then I would come back, and they'd have things stacked up.
The boys wouldn't try to take care of it.
They'd say, well, now Dr. Anderson's out of town, but he'll be back here Tuesday, and we'll set you up for Tuesday.
All right, that's fine.
I would fight it for a few days, and then I was gone again.
But I wouldn't take anything for it.
It is a wonderful experience.
But like I say, I wouldn't do it again at all.
Well, AVMA was 100 years old then, and it's a lot older now.
You know, old Dick Turk told me I had just been elected in Detroit.
And naturally, I...
He was on the board for a long time.
Yes, yes.
He followed me on the board, too.
And I was writing notes.
Well, I've got to do this, I've got to do that.
He said, Dan, how old is this?
I said, man, it's going to be 100 years old next year, and I've got a lot of things to do here, a lot of things to think about, centennial celebration and all that stuff.
He said, just relax.
You can't possibly destroy it in two years.
He said, just relax.
You can't possibly destroy it in two years.
Dan, isn't it a shame that we didn't sit down and get a two-hour interview from him?
Back before, you know, he wasn't the same Turk the last five or ten years.
No, no.
You're talking about the original.
Yeah, the original Dick Turk.
He was sick the last ten years.
Yeah, yeah.
Unfortunately.
You know...
He should never have been re-elected to that board up there as a second term.
He was not in physical condition or mental condition to do it, but I wasn't one to say.
You know, we'd been friends all those years, and he wanted to go back, and I said, well, what the hell.
Don't you think Charlie Huff was pretty good for TVMA?
Uh-uh.
He might have been good for TVMA, but he wasn't worth a darn for me.
And I'll tell you what.
I would...
I'll tell you what I'd do.
I'd recommend it.
I told him at the time I'd recommend him for any other job than anybody else, but I thought he ought to be out of the TV and that.
Is that back in 62?
No.
No, Charlie Huff.
They didn't.
Just here, just before they fired him.
Oh, I'm talking about recently.
Yeah.
But you know, he was there for 17 years.
And he got worse all the time.
I don't know what Charlie...

quiet charlie did it but he screwed me around about three or four times and without any reason about the last year he was there and finally i just got on his tail and and uh oh uh several little things and finally they made me an honorary life member what do they call it and sent me a certificate and didn't even sign it which it didn't make any difference you know but uh uh
uh in the beginning yes in the beginning i i think charles uh charlie uh probably did an outstanding job but uh as all executive secretaries do eventually they get to where they
I guess we bring it on them because we allow them to do this.
They get to where it's, I'm doing this and I'm running this.
Not for the board, I'm doing it, you know, I'm doing it.
And eventually they'll make enough people mad, like he did me, that they'll have to move on.
That's the story of executive secretaries.
Well, my only complaint was that I think
Executive secretaries are never supposed to last that long, you know.
It's just like city managers.
Yeah, yeah.
10 years is probably the top, and 12 years is too much, and 15 is way too much.
That's right, that's right.
But, well, looking back on your practice life, what do you think of it?
Well, if I had it to do over again, I wouldn't change it a whole lot.
I've been greatly blessed.
I really have.
I'm not a wealthy person, but I've made some good investments.
I got involved in a little old bank out here 20 or 25 years ago and made investments in it.
And then I got in
involved with Texas phenethiazine, and it eventually worked out all right.
In fact, I just got paid off.
We sold that thing on credit.
I just got my money last fall.
But anyway, all in all, and my practice, I just...
wouldn't change my practice a whole lot.
I've got friends, I've got acquaintances, I've got clients that have been doing business for 40 years, and I've got...
I worked for the father, I worked for the... Then I worked for the son, and then I'm now working for the grandchildren.
For the grandchildren, yeah.
And... Oh, we haven't made everybody happy, but we...
I'll...
I'm not ashamed of the crowd I'm running with.
Well, that's wonderful.
